Scandals such as Birmingham's pluralities were the outcome of a general decline in the character oi the English hierarchy. Birmingham was a layman in possession of many benefices. Gascoigne mentions an· other, a physician, married (p.43). and in possession os two deaneries, two prebends, and a great rectory, who was seldom resident in one of these five benefices, and never in the others, and therefore one of those dumb dogs of whom the prophet Isaiah speaks.
